      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here's the `reflect` function that calculates the reflection vector based on the incident vector and surface normal:\n\n```python\ndef reflect(incident, normal):\n    \"\"\"\n    Calculate the reflection vector of an incident vector at a surface.\n\n    Parameters:\n    incident (list): Incident vector.\n    normal (list): Surface normal.\n\n    Returns:\n    list: Reflected vector.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Calculate the dot product of incident and normal vectors\n    dot_product = sum(x*y for x, y in zip(incident, normal))\n    \n    # Calculate the projection of incident onto normal\n    projection = [dot_product]*len(normal)\n    \n    # Calculate the component of incident perpendicular to normal\n    perpendicular_component = [x - y*dot_product for x, y in zip(incident, normal)]\n    \n    # The reflected vector is twice the perpendicular component of incident\n    reflected_vector = [2*x for x in perpendicular_component]\n    \n    return reflected_vector\n```\n\nThis function works by first calculating the dot product between the incident vector and the surface normal. Then it calculates the projection of the incident vector onto the normal vector. The component of the incident vector perpendicular to the normal is then subtracted from the incident vector to get the",
